The Minister of Mines and Steel Development, Arc, Olamilekan Adegbite has stated that involvement of the private sector in waterway transportation will boost commerce and trade to a very large extent in the country. The Minister disclosed this while overseeing in his office on Tuesday the signing of a Memorandum of Understanding (MoU) facilitated by the Nigerian Export and Import  (NEXIM) Bank between Sealink and Ajaokuta Steel Company (ASC) on behalf of the federal government on internal waterways transportation. The Minister and the Sole Administrator, Ajaokuta Steel Company, Engr Abdul-Akaba Sumaila, signed on the federal government side, while the managing director (MD), NEXIM Bank, Abba Bello, and the Chairman, Sealink, Mrs Dabney Shal-Holma, signed for Sealink. Sealink is out for the evacuation of cargoes and imports through the internal waterways in Nigeria. Ajaokuta was part of the MoU signing because its jetty is one of those lined up to be used as a landing base for the goods, especially imports that will be transported inland through waterways in the country. In his remark prior to the signing, the Minister said, “This will serve to promote trade and commerce. We have not been able to regulate the weight of vehicles on our road, and most times, the trucks are overloaded, thus spoiling the roads. That is why the federal government is now focusing on rail transportation. I think this is a giant stride for the country in terms of commerce and logistics.” The Minister noted that there are about 31 states in Nigeria that have access to the internal waterways, adding “I salute the entrepreneurship and doggedness of this NEXIM Bank-led team.”